Performing a similar calculation for the number density and the chiral density number, defined as $n=\langle \psi^\dag \psi \rangle $ and $n_5=\langle \psi^\dag \gamma_5 \psi \rangle$, respectively. 
The densities can be, as in the case of the currents, written in terms of the number density of each chirality:
\begin{eqnarray}
n\left(x^2\right) &=& \nu\left(x^2-x^2_+\right)+\nu\left(x^2-x^2_-\right)\;,
\nonumber\\
n_5\left(x^2\right) &=& \nu\left(x^2-x^2_+\right)-\nu\left(x^2-x^2_-\right)\;,
\end{eqnarray}
with the function $\nu$ defined as

\begin{eqnarray} \nonumber
\nu(\eta)=- \frac{eB}{\pi}\sum_n \int_{-\infty} ^\infty ds\ r_s(\omega_n \mu)\  (\omega_n -i\mu) \\
 \left[\frac{1}{eBs\ \tan(eBs)} \right] ^{1/2}\ {\rm e}^{-i\left(s(\omega_n -i\mu)^{2}+ eB\ \tan(eBs)\ \eta^2 \right)}.
 \label{eq:density}
\end{eqnarray}
In the strong field limit,  after rotation of the proper time $s\to -is$ and taking $\tan(eBs)\to -i\tanh(eBs)\approx -i$, 
we obtain the same result as for the current density (up to a unit charge factor $e$, of course). In Fig.~\ref{fig:density} we show that our approximation is in agreement with the full expression in Eq.~(\ref{eq:density}) in this regime. 

